On September 30, 1928, exactly 90 years ago, British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced an unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin ushered in the era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the extraction of penicillin from mold was not Fleming's first discovery.
A few years earlier, he had a cold and sowed mucus from his nose on a petri dish, and after a few days he found that the bacteria had been killed.
It was almost by accident that they discovered penicillin.
Fleming's name was included in the list of the 100 most outstanding people in human history.
