Kosachev: Russia was virtually absent from the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly
The head of the Federation Council's Committee on International Affairs, Konstantin Kosachev, considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly to be a success for Russia and does not rule out that it will be a turning point in Russia's perception of Russia as an integral participant in solving global problems.
"The uniqueness of the current 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric to which we have become almost accustomed in recent years in relation to Russia, was now much more muted", the senator said in an interview published on Sunday by the "Russian newspaper".
He explained that in previous years, Russia has been "sometimes singled out as one of the three main threats to humanity, whether alongside Ebola, climate change or terrorism, Russia was in that number, at least in the narrative of a group of Western countries that were quite unanimous on this issue".
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, "there was virtually no negative Russia".
"If you carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Germany, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, at least the chorus was not completely accurate", the politician noted, noting that Russia "was no longer a wall against which tennis balls are trained".
The head of the relevant committee of the Federation Council does not exclude that this indicates a trend that, in his opinion, "will highlight the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although in full this trend may be manifested in a year, in two, in three".
"I don't rule out that this session could be a turning point in some sense", Kosachev admitted, explaining that "there are too many examples of how Russia's involvement can move forward in international affairs".
He cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea as examples.
"Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time", the parliamentarian added.
This is due, he believes, to the emergence of "an adequate, healthy perception of Russia as not just possible - an integral participant in solving the global problems of the modern world".
"I don't want to be wrong, but I have a feeling that we are passing somewhere a point where the movement will no longer be a movement backwards, it will be a movement forward", he added.
Another "interesting and important sensation" in this context, Kosachev called "the request for a Russian vision of how the modern world should develop".
"I attended many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [to the General Assembly session] Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two or five years ago, no one was interested in the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, the situation is different now", said the chairman of the Committee of the Federation.
In his opinion, this is due to the fact that "the so-called new liberal order, which is personified with the West, does not have answers to the questions of how to solve world problems due to the apparent shortage of ideas in the global space, the shortage of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problem of terrorism, the problem of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, the problem of migration".
"And here the request for a Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious", Kosachev said, emphasizing that he considers this session "successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia".
