The ADG is the second most popular music group in Germany.
The anti-immigrant Alternative for Germany is setting another popularity record, and Angela Merkel's ratings are dropping.
Apparently, Germans are getting really tired of Angela Merkel's immigration policy, which has made the country a coveted destination for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
This is most clearly shown by the latest opinion polls, which show that the anti-immigrant Alternative for Germany party is gaining in popularity, while the ruling bloc of Merkel and Seehofer is losing ground.
This week, the ADG broke another record, climbing to the second place in the popularity ranking.
The right-wing conservatives, with 17 percent of the popular vote, managed to overtake the social democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The one percentage point gap can be blamed on a statistical error, but it is worth noting that the AfD, which was formed in 2013 by a small group of Eurosceptic economists, has managed to become a serious political force.
The leadership in the overall standings is still held by the ruling bloc of the CSU/CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points - back in April, the support for Angela Merkel's bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German chancellor, who is heading the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also declining.
Today, 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel, down 7 percent from last year.
The Social Democrats are followed by the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
The evolution of the Alternative
The party "Alternative for Germany" was created in September 2012 on the basis of the group "Alternative Choice 2013", which included people from the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government's course, but at first only dealt with economic issues, including the problems of the euro and interaction within the EU.
The group opposed Germany's "sponsorship" of the weak EU economies, and did not rule out the possibility of a return to the Deutsche Mark and the country's complete exit from the European Union.
Amidst the deepening immigration crisis, the AdG's political platform has expanded.
In 2013, the group became a full-fledged party, which took over the niche of the Eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
At the last parliamentary election in 2017, the AfD managed to make its way into the Bundestag for the first time, winning 94 seats (out of 709).
Two Alternative for Germany members have won seats in the European Parliament.
