Called the death of the universe.
The universe is still about 140 billion years old, ten times the age of the observable world, or about 13.8 billion years.
The study by an international team of scientists has been uploaded to the electronic preprint library arXiv.org and is being submitted for publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, reports the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
The researchers came to this conclusion by observing some ten million galaxies with the Hyper Suprime-Cam (HSC) camera of the Subaru telescope.
By tracking the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 percent of the energy-mass of the observable world, scientists working within the standard cosmological model ΛCDM (Λ Cold Dark Matter) estimated the expansion rate of the universe, which turned out to be slightly slower than previously thought.
The Subaru Observatory press release notes that the observations have provided a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the universe, and the inclusion of European Planck space telescope data has clarified the limitations imposed on the ΛCDM parameters.
In July, scientists modeled a possible end of the universe.
Three years earlier, their colleagues had presented new arguments that the observable world would end in 22 billion years as a result of the Big Bang.
