Scientist talks about possible scientific program of Russian expedition to the Moon
The head of the Institute of Space Research of the Russian Academy of Sciences, corresponding member of the Russian Academy of Sciences Anatoly Petrukovich told RIA Novosti about a possible program of scientific research for Russian cosmonauts on the Moon.
He said that the scientific community is currently working on the development of such directions.
"There is no consolidated opinion yet", he said.
He noted that one option would be to place a low-frequency radio telescope on the far side of the moon, which would avoid interference from Earth.
"This is the only place where such a telescope can be deployed for the study of cosmic sources of radio radiation", added Petruković.
He also thinks the moon could be used for robotics testing, for building on local resources.
He also believes that astronauts should be involved in the search for primitive organisms on Earth's moon.
This could help us determine how life emerges on planets.
Earlier, the head of the Roscosmos Corporation said that in an optimistic scenario, the Russian Federation could carry out a manned flight to the Moon by 2030.
