The main Macedonian oppositionist refused to vote in the referendum
In Macedonia, a referendum on the issue of an intergovernmental treaty with Greece on renaming the Republic of Macedonia will be held on Sunday, September 30.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: "Do you support membership in the EU and NATO by accepting the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Hellenic Republic?"
However, the leader of the leading opposition party, Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity (IMRO-DPMNE), Christian Mitskoski, said that he would not vote in the referendum.
As the party's press secretary Naum Stoilkovsky explained, Mitskowski decided to abstain from voting to express his disagreement with the treaty, which he considers "pernicious".
According to the spokesman, the current referendum is about renaming the country and nothing more, while the party's strategic goal is to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago, Macedonian President Georgi Ivanov also refused to participate in the September 30 referendum.
He explained that the name for the country he chose 27 years ago in the independence referendum. The Macedonian leader considers the renaming of the country a negative factor.
"A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is being created", Ivanov said.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav republic - the Republic of North Macedonia - was signed by the foreign ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a ceremony on the shore of Lake Prespa, which marks the border between the two countries.
The agreement should resolve the long-standing dispute over the country's name, as well as Skopje's path to NATO and the EU, TASS reminds.
A fire broke out at the restaurant of Istanbul's "meme chef"
