Macedonians are preparing to vote in a referendum on joining the EU and NATO, with the country's name changed.
The agreement to rename the former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia to the Republic of North Macedonia was reached on 17 June as a result of long negotiations with neighboring Greece, which refused to recognize the right of its northern neighbor to be called Macedonia, seeing in such a name an attempt on the same name Greek province and Greek history.
Lupko Petkovski, political scientist: "Thanks to this agreement, Macedonia or North Macedonia gets the right to a better future, the hope for social change.
And Greece will claim its right to the past.
There are no perfect agreements.
They are the result of difficult compromises that cannot make everyone happy".
The ruling Social Democrats led by Prime Minister Zoran Zaev are in favor of renaming the country.
Opposition is the conservative opposition and the country's President, Georgi Ivanov.
According to journalist Tsvetin Chilimanov, Macedonia has no sense to join the EU - it is enough to have partnership relations with it: "Many of those who do not like the agreement believe that the current socialist government headed by Zaev is imposed from outside to change the name of the country.
